Floyd-Warshall Algorithm

The Floyd-Warshall algorithm is an All-Pairs Shortest Path (APSP) algorithm used to find the shortest weighted distances between every pair of vertices in a directed or undirected graph.

Key Advantages:
Unlike Bellman-Ford or Dijkstra which are single-source, Floyd-Warshall calculates the shortest paths between all pairs of nodes simultaneously.
It handles negative edge weights and can detect the presence of negative weight cycles.
Extremely simple to implement due to its 3-nested loop structure.

Complexity:
Time Complexity: O(V^3) (where V is vertices).
Space Complexity: O(V^2) for the 2D distance matrix.

How it Works (Dynamic Programming Approach) // only for revision purpose not detiled steps
1. We initialize a 2D distance matrix where dist[i][j] is the weight of the edge from i to j. If there is no edge, it is set to infinity (1e9). The diagonal dist[i][i] is set to 0.
2. We use three nested loops. The outermost loop picks an intermediate vertex 'k'.
3. The inner loops pick a source 'i' and destination 'j'. For every pair (i, j), we check if going through 'k' offers a shorter path: dist[i][j] = min(dist[i][j], dist[i][k] + dist[k][j]).
4. After all iterations, the matrix contains the shortest distances. If any diagonal element dist[i][i] becomes negative, it proves a negative weight cycle exists.

Q: Why is the 'k' loop (intermediate node) the outermost loop? //follow up and important comceptual questions with simple and small explanation
The algorithm builds solutions incrementally. In the k-th iteration, it finds the shortest path between all pairs (i, j) using only vertices from 0 to k as intermediate nodes. If 'k' were the innermost loop, we would only evaluate paths with a single specific intermediate node at a time, failing to chain paths together properly through multiple intermediate nodes.

Implementation (Standard)

void floyd_warshall(vector<vector<int>>& matrix) {
    int n = matrix.size();
    
    // Preparation: Assuming -1 means no edge in input matrix. 
    // Convert -1 to infinity (1e9) and diagonal to 0.
    for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
        for (int j = 0; j < n; j++) {
            if (matrix[i][j] == -1) matrix[i][j] = 1e9;
            if (i == j) matrix[i][j] = 0;
        }
    }

    // Core logic: 3 nested loops
    for (int k = 0; k < n; k++) {
        for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
            for (int j = 0; j < n; j++) {
                // If both i->k and k->j are reachable, check if this path is shorter
                if (matrix[i][k] != 1e9 && matrix[k][j] != 1e9) {
                    matrix[i][j] = min(matrix[i][j], matrix[i][k] + matrix[k][j]);
                }
            }
        }
    }
    
    // Optional: Convert 1e9 back to -1 for unreachable paths
    for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
        for (int j = 0; j < n; j++) {
            if (matrix[i][j] == 1e9) matrix[i][j] = -1;
        }
    }
}
